BMW, the sole distributor of BMW automobiles in the United States, allows certain employees to use BMW automobiles as a fringe benefit of employment. Under BMW\rquote s automobile fringe benefit policy as it existed in 1988 and 1989, BMW assigned a particular \u8220\'3fseries\u8221\'3f of BMW models to an employee based on the employee\rquote s job title. For example, BMW assigned BMW \u8220\'3f7 Series\u8221\'3f automobiles to vice-presidents, \u8220\'3f5 Series\u8221\'3f automobiles to department managers, and \u8220\'3f3 Series\u8221\'3f automobiles to section managers and field employees. However, if a model was in short supply or oversupply, an employee may have been assigned a model different from that normally assigned to his or her job title. Employees do not have freedom of choice concerning the color and features of the vehicles assigned to them; rather, the assignment is made by BMW based on existing inventory supply. An employee\rquote s use of a BMW vehicle is a privilege that may be revoked if the employee fails to operate the assigned vehicle in accordance with BMW\rquote s guidelines.
